## ðŸ” Host Discovery with Nmap

The Nmap tool is essential for network scanning and host discovery. Here are key commands for finding live hosts on a network.

### 1. Basic Nmap Command Structure

| Action                                     | Command Syntax 

| **General Scan**                           | `nmap [Scan Options] target` 
| **Ping Scan (Host Discovery)**             | `nmap -sn [target]` 
| **Example (Single IP)**                    | `nmap -sn 192.168.1.1` 
| **Help/Manual**                            | `nmap -h` (for quick menu) or `man nmap` (for full manual page) 

---

### 2. Checking Your IP Address

* Use the command `ifconfig` to **check your own IP address** before scanning.

---

### 3. Scanning a Range or Subnet

You can scan an entire subnet (CIDR notation) to quickly discover all live hosts:

| Action                                       | Command Example                    | Note 

| **Scan Subnet (CIDR)**                       | `nmap -sn 10.1.0.0/24`             | Scans all 256 addresses in that range. 
| **Scan Subnet (Specific Range)**             | `nmap -sn 10.10.22.0/24 --send-ip` | The `--send-ip` option is non-standard for basic host discovery and might                                                                                           imply a specific scenario or Nmap version.

---

### 4. Scanning Multiple IP Addresses

Nmap offers flexible ways to scan multiple targets:

* **Using a Range (Dashes):**
    * `nmap -sn 10.4.23.227-240` (Scans from 227 through 240)
* **Using a Range (Space-Separated):**
    * `nmap -sn 10.4.23.227 10.4.23.228`
* **Using an Input File (Best for efficiency):**
    1.  **Create a file:** Use a text editor like `vim` to create a file (e.g., **targets.txt**).
    2.  **Add IPs:** Put one IP address or IP range per line inside the file.
    3.  **Scan from file:** `nmap -sn -iL targets.txt`

> **Note:** The **`-sn`** option stands for "skip port scan" or "no port scan," which means Nmap will only perform **host discovery** (ping scan) and not attempt to find open ports. This is much **faster** for simply finding live hosts.

---

ðŸ§  Host Discovery with Nmap

ðŸ”¹ Basic Ping Scan
> nmap -sn 192.168.1.1        # Ping scan
> nmap -h                     # Help menu
> man nmap                    # Manual page

ðŸ”¹ Check Your IP
> ifconfig                               # Check your IP
> nmap -sn 10.1.0.0/24                   # Basic network sweep
> nmap -sn 10.10.22.0/24 --send-ip       # Sends raw IP packets instead of Ethernet frames

ðŸ”¹ Scan Multiple IP Addresses
> nmap -sn 10.4.23.227 10.4.23.228
> nmap -sn 10.4.23.227-240

ðŸ”¹ Efficient Scanning Using a File:
vim targets.txt               # Save IPs or ranges in this file
> nmap -sn -iL targets.txt    # Scan all listed targets

âš™ï¸ Advanced Host Discovery

ðŸ”¹ TCP SYN Scan
> nmap -sn -PS 10.4.23.227      # Sends TCP SYN packet to port 80 to check if host is alive

ðŸ”¹ TCP ACK Scan
> nmap -sn -PA 10.4.23.227      # Sends TCP ACK packet to bypass stateless firewalls

ðŸ”¹ ICMP Specific Scan
> nmap -sn -PE 10.4.23.227 --send-ip                           # Performs standard ICMP ping discovery
> nmap -sn -v -T4 10.4.23.227                                  # Uses default discovery methods (usually ICMP Echo + TCP SYN to port 443)
> nmap -sn -PS21,22,25,80,445,3389,8080 -T4 10.4.20.217        # TCP SYN ping on specified ports (host discovery only)
> sudo nmap -sS -p 21,22,25,80,445,3389,8080 -T4 10.4.20.217   # Actual port scanning (not host discovery)

> nmap -sn -PS21,22,25,80,445,3389,8080 10.4.20.217            # First discover if host is up
> sudo nmap -sS -p 21,22,25,80,445,3389,8080 10.4.20.217       # Then scan ports

ðŸ”¹ Note: PU137,138 â†’ UDP ping on ports 137 and 138

nmap -Pn 10.5.18.135            # Force scanning even if host seems down
nmap -Pn -p 443 10.5.18.135     # Check closed ports (to detect firewall presence) 
                                #If output shows filtered, it indicates a firewall is present.
